post_text:
An important message below from Dr. Sutfin today. We've shared our beliefs before and thought this would be a good time to share them again. Our beliefs are the foundation of our district's strategic plan. They are our fundamental values, ethical codes, overriding convictions and principles.

- Each individual has worth.
- Individuals are responsible for their actions.
- Our greatest resource is people.
- Diversity enriches life.
- All people can learn.
- High expectations promote higher achievement.
- Achievement builds self-esteem; self-esteem promotes achievement.
- Shaping and developing character is the shared responsibility of the individual, family, school, and community.
- All people are entitled to a safe, caring, and respectful environment.
- Responsible risk-taking is essential for growth.
- Educated and engaged citizens are necessary to sustain our democratic society.
- All schools are accountable to the community.
- Public education benefits the entire community and is the shared responsibility of all.
- Excellence is worth the investment.

May 13 at 8:05 PM ·

And just like that 1st grade has come to an end. Final class zoom and “see ya laters” with the friendships that were formed during their time together. The time where they sat side by side, walked in single file lines, and raced across monkey bars or down the slide. Such a bittersweet time in history that will stick with these little learners forever and become a part of their story. Our last few weeks haven’t been normal but they have been full of new opportunity. Thanks for helping us through it Millard Public Schools! #proud2bMPS

post_text: Think you can't come together on Zoom? Just listen! #Proud2bMPS
shared_text:
Drew Firkins
April 24 at 6:18 PM ·

I started an a cappella group this year at Russell Middle School called "Wolfgang" (I'm very proud of the name 😉). We had been working on this song for several months and were getting ready to take it to an a cappella competition before school was cancelled for the year. The kids and I have continued to meet on Zoom after school hours and put in tons of time practicing and recording for this 'performance', and I got to exercise my music tech chops putting it all together (thanks Tom Larson!)

Here is Wolfgang's "Fire on Fire" by Sam Smith! Happy new music Friday! 😁

Rohwer Elementary School: Sandi Dawson knows all of our families. She has an amazing memory that she knows student and parent names and recognizes everyone when they come into the office. She opened up Rohwer Elementary and has a wonderful historical perspective of the building. Sandi takes care of all of us in the building. Any time that anyone needs something, we always go to Sandi because we know that she will help us with whatever is needed. She is a tremendous asset to the Rohwer community.
We ❤ our Administrative Professional #AdministrativeProfessionalsWeek

post_text:
Millard West High School is one of the four schools to be honored for outstanding in theatre education by Educational Theatre Association Congrats!!
"The Millard West High School theatre program home to Thespian Troupe 5483 under the direction of Brooke Phillips was recognized for fostering a collaborative theatre environment where students are empowered to work together. Collaboration is at the core of Millard’s theatre program. Thespians support other fine arts programs including Millard West’s band, choir, and orchestra to ensure theatre is accessible to all students. During the musical production of Bring It On, a third of the cast came from Millard West’s cheerleading squad. Phillips is most proud of the community theatre partnership between Troupe 5483 and the Improv Academy, an improv program piloted by Millard West and 88 Improv where students develop stories, think on their feet, and develop characters. She says, “We are a service-oriented drama club. We work to put on quality shows that students and adults alike would be interested in seeing.”
https://tinyurl.com/s6qcqgc

Blood drives continue to be canceled at an alarming rate—nearly 10,000 so far. Blood drive hosts like Wheeler Elementary School in partnership with Water's Edge Church, are asked to maintain scheduled drives whenever possible as new locations are found to replace all the cancelled drives. To date there are about 300,000 fewer blood donations scheduled.

Wheeler Elementary School is hosting its blood drive on April 2nd. The Red Cross looking for about 130 blood donor heroes and so far 90 amazing people have stepped up. Help fill the empty spots. Sign up now!
https://www.redcrossblood.org/give.html/drive-results?zipSponsor=WheelerElementary&fbclid=IwAR3oRJ-yJXj6gN6-ZsEd0aEqUisWhPgoXLQzejOlogR4AF9-6cp0CCaxMoU

post_text:
Millard Public Schools is happy to lend a helping hand to our community partners by donating UV lockers to CHI Health to be used in their facilities state wide.
A former MWHS student remembered using these lockers in her high school chemistry class and reached out. We were happy to help.
These lockers will be used to disinfect gear.
To all of our healthcare professionals, we are thinking of you. Thank you for the work you are doing to keep our community safe.

Community Meal Distribution:
In an effort to address the needs of families feeling the financial impact of the Coronavirus pandemic, the NorthStar Foundation, The Learning Community of Douglas and Sarpy Counties, and Millard Public Schools will be distributing evening meals from three drive up sites. Community Meals will be distributed this week for families with school age children. Distribution will include meals for two adults and one meal for each child present in the car plus one additional child’s meal. No identification or sign in will be required.

shared_text:
NOISE
March 12 at 3:15 PM ·

History is repeating with Hunter Sallis, an All-State Millard North High School player, rated as the No. 20 prospect nationally in the 2021 class and USA Basketball team minicamp invitee. His mother, Jessica Haynes, rose to basketball prominence in her time at Omaha Central High School.

Millard North won its district to earn the No. 2 seed in the state tournament. Millard North plays Papillion La Vista South today at 7 p.m. at Pinnacle Bank Arena.

Coronavirus precautions will prevent the general public from watching him in action, but you can bet that his mother and family will be there to see him try to repeat history in Lincoln. You can listen or watch via streaming media for more.

Read NOISE coverage: "Basketball legacy binds legend, Jessica Haynes, and her basketball star, Hunter Sallis" bit.ly/Sallis-Haynes

shared_text:
Kelly Ludgate Whisinnand
March 4 at 11:24 PM ·

Millard is offering 5 show choir camps this summer!!! Why Show Choir? Let me tell you! Show choir builds a strong sense of family. Through movement and music your child experiences joy, practices grit, gains true friendships, learns hard work, and simply has so much fun!!! In show choir, EVERYONE is important and no one is ever sitting on the bench! Why come to Millard??? The directors putting on these camps are certified teachers with years of experience showing children the love of music!!!! WE LOVE WHAT WE DO!!! We are so passionate about students and show choir!!! Check out the flyers below and email one of the directors to get registered!!! We can’t wait to make music with your child this summer! #Proud2bMPS
Megan Tantillo, Braxton Carr, Elizabeth Fritton
Eric Engstrom, Lori Brown, Brittany McCleery
Allie Hoffmann, Haley Allen
